<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870304-0004 </DOCNO><HL> Sens. Dole and Biden MoveToward Presidential Bids</HL><DD> 03/04/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> CONGRESS (CNG) </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Senate Republican Leader Robert Dole of Kansas and Democratic Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware took first steps toward avowed campaigns for their parties' presidential nominations.    Mr. Dole announced formation of an exploratory committee that will handle his campaign's organizing; Mr. Biden, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, established a formal campaign committee.    Mr. Dole selected Robert Ellsworth, a former ambassador to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization and Kansas congressman, to head his panel. Mr. Dole isn't expected to announce his candidacy formally before summer.    Other Republicans who already have such committees in operation include Vice President George Bush, Rep. Jack Kemp of New York, and television evangelist Pat Robertson. Republican Gov. Pierre du Pont of Delaware already has declared himself a formal candidate.    Besides Mr. Biden, Democrats who have set up campaign committees include Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, who has formally announced his candidacy, and former Gov. Bruce Babbitt of Arizona, who plans to announce Tuesday.    Former Sen. Gary Hart of Colorado has set up an exploratory committee; he plans to formally announce his candidacy April 13. </TEXT></DOC>